setTimeout(function() {
    var clozeBoxes = document.querySelector(".cloze cloze2_w");
    var elements = document.querySelectorAll("cloze2." + clozeBoxes.className);

<script>
/* --- DO NOT DELETE OR EDIT THIS SCRIPT --- */
setTimeout(function() {
    var clozeBoxes = document.querySelector(".cloze cloze2_w");
    var elements = document.querySelectorAll("cloze2." + clozeBoxes.className);
    for(var i = 0 ; i < elements.length ; i++) {
        elements[i].classList.add("cloze");
        elements[i].style.display="inline";
    }
}, 0);
/* --- DO NOT DELETE OR EDIT THIS SCRIPT --- */
</script>



{{cloze:Text}}

{{#Hide others on the back side}}
<style>
cloze2 {
    display: none;
}

cloze2_w {
    display: inline-block;
    width: 5em;
    height: 1em;
    background-color: #ffeba2;
}

.cloze cloze2 {
    display: inline;
}

.cloze cloze2_w {
    display: none;
}

cloze2.reveal-cloze2 {
    display: inline;
}

cloze2_w.reveal-cloze2 {
    display: none;
}

.cloze2-toggle {
    -webkit-appearance: none;
    display: block;
    font-size: 1.3em;
    height: 2em;
    background-color: #ffffff;
    width: 100%;
    margin-top: 20px;
}

.cloze2-toggle:active {
    background-color: #ffffaa;
}
</style>

<script>
function toggle() {
var elements = document.querySelectorAll('cloze2, cloze2_w');
    for(var i = 0 ; i < elements.length ; i++) {
        elements[i].classList.toggle('reveal-cloze2');
    }
}
</script>

<button class='cloze2-toggle' onclick='toggle()'>Toogle mask</button>
{{/Hide others on the back side}}

fields: What are the functions of connective tissue? (There are 5--D.A.M.S.S.)

1. Defense/protection of the body
2. Attachemnt for epithelia
3. Medium for exchange (nutrients, waste, metabolites)
4. Structural support
5. Storage for energy (fats)
{{c1::Fibroblasts::type of cell}} are derived from mesenchymal cells.
Inactive {{c2::fibroblasts}} (sometimes called {{c1::fibrocytes}}) are smaller, with less evidence of protein machinery

‚ùëmast cells
20 to 30 mm in diameter
{{c1::ovoid}}, with central spherical nucleus
derive from {{c2::marrow}} precursors
cytoplasm filled with {{c4::basophilic}} granules containing {{c3::heparin, histamine, proteases}} and other compounds
activated by binding of {{c5::IgE::An immunoglobulin}} to Fc receptors in response to the presence of foreign antigens (e.g. pollen, bee venom, drugs)

‚ùëplasma cells
activated {{c1::B lymphocytes}}
{{c2::ovoid}} cells, with eccentrically placed nuclei with ‚Äú{{c3::clock face}}‚Äù or ‚Äú{{c3::cartwheel}}‚Äù appearance
intensely basophilic, lots of {{c4::RER}}
produce {{c5::antibodies}}
Macrophages are irregular in shape, and often possess {{c1::fliopodia}}

What conditions correctly describes a macrophage?
A. Basophilic, containing vacuoles and granules, centrally located nucleus that is indented and heterochromatic
B. Eosinophilic, containing vacuoles and granules, eccentric nucleus that is indented and heterochromatic
C. Basophilic, containing vacuoles and granules, eccentric nucleus that is not indented and euchromatic
D. Basophilic, containing vacuoles and granules, eccentric nucleus that is indented and heterochromatic
D. Basophilic, containing vacuoles and granules, eccentric nucleus that is indented and heterochromatic
Macrophages are members of the {{c1::mononuclear phagocyte system (MPS)}} and it arises from {{c1::stem cells in bone marrow}}
{{c1::Monocytes}} mature into macrophages under the influence of {{c1::M-CSF}}

What is the nomenclature for macrophages in each of the locations:
Liver - {{c1::Kupffer cells}}
Lungs - {{c2::Dust cells or alveolar macrophages}}
Skin, mucosa - {{c3::Langerhans cells}}
Blood - {{c4::monocytes}}
Connective tissues - {{c5::macrophages}}
What are other (not macrophage) MPS cells named in the bone? Brain?
{{c1::Myofibroblasts}} are sometimes considered to be intermediates between {{c2::fibroblasts::cell type}} and {{c2::smooth muscle cells::cell type}}.
{{c1::Myofibroblasts::cell type}} possess bundles of actin and myosin like smooth muscle cells, but shape is similar to fibroblasts.
What type of cell is abundant in wound healing?
What cell type is found in periodontal ligaments and thought to be assosciated with tooth eruption?
Myofibroblasts can be found in {{c1::periodontal ligaments::area in oral cavity}}
Pericytes surround endothelial cells of {{c1::capillaries}} and {{c1::small venules}}
Pericytes can differentiate into vascular {{c1::smooth muscle cells}}, {{c1::fibroblasts}}, {{c1::adipocytes}}, {{c1::neural cells}}, {{c1::glial cells}}, and {{c1::skeletal muscle fibers}}.
These cells are surrounded by basal lamina, but are separate from connective tissue.
These cells are intermediates between endothelial cells and smooth muscle cells:
T/F Pericytes are intermediates between fibroblasts and smooth muscle cells.

False: 
Pericytes are intermediates between endothelial cells and smooth muscle cells
Myofibroblasts are intermediates between fibroblasts and smooth muscle cells
Adipose cells are derived from {{c1::mesenchymal cells}}
T/F Adipose cells are post-mitotic, terminally differntiated
What are the functions of Adipose cells?

1. synthesis and storage of triglycerides 
2. production of estrogen and leptin
The two types of adipose fat cells are: {{c1::unilocular}} and {{c1::multilocular}}
{{c1::Unilocular}} fat cells are one single lipid droplet that fills the entire cell. Known as {{c1::"white fat" }}
{{c1::Multilocular}} fat cells contain many small lipid droplets in the cytoplasm. Known as {{c1::"brown fat"}}
{{c1::Multilocular}} fat cells have large numbers of {{c2::mitochondria}} and are involved in heat generation.

{{c1::Unimolecular::Unilocular or multilocular}} adipocytes are {{c2::spherical::shape}}, cells appear polyhedral when packed together {{c2::("chicken wire")::What do these cells look like when packed together?}}; nucelus and cytoplasm are displaced {{c3::peripherally:: location}}, golgi is present, sparse {{c4::mitochondria and RER::what organelles are sparse}}, abundant free ribosomes.
Multilocular adipocytes are {{c1::smaller::smaller or larger}} than unilocular adipocytes.
{{c1::Multilocular}} adipocytes are more polygonal, nucleus is {{c2::central::location}} and sperical, multiple small lipid droplets, SER, no {{c2::RER::organelle}}.
what is the role of macrophages
phagocytosis of senescent, damaged and dead cells, and cellular debris, foreign substances and microorganisms, and also act as antigen-presenting cells (APC's)
Mast cells are {{c1::ovoid::type of shape}} with central {{c2::spherical::type of shape}} nucleus.
The cytoplams of mast cells contains basophilic granules. What are the common ones?
Mast cells are activated by binding of {{c1::IgE::IgE/Fc}} to {{c2::Fc::IgE/Fc}} receptors in response to the presence of {{c3::foreign::non-foreign/foreign}} antigens.

What kind of connective tissue is present in embryos but can also be found in adults? Where?
Embryonic connective tissue (mesenchymal connective tissue). Found in tooth pulp
{{c1::Mesenchymal connective tissue}}- formed of {{c2::mesenchymal cells}} and gel-like {{c3::ground substance}} with {{c4::reticular fibers}}
What are some characteristics of mesenchymal cells?
Ovoid, with a prominent nucleolus and sparse pale-staining cytoplasm. Known for frequent mitoses
How can you tell when connective tissue are multiplying through microscopy?
Because they will be clumping, the morphology will change, and the number of cells will increase drastically
What kind of tissue is loose, amorphous, contains stem cells, and found only in the umbilical cord (known as "Wharton's jelly)?
Why is loose connective tissue called loose?
Because of the amount of ground substance that is in it, which doesn't stain well
What are some examples of loose connective tissue?
Fibroblasts, adipocytes, macrophages, mast cells, undifferentiated cells, collagen, reticular elastic fibers
Where can the loose connective tissue be found?
dermis, mesothelium, adventitia of blood vessels, stroma of glands, lamina propria of digestive and respiratory tracts, fascias
Loose connective tissues are also called what?

‚ùëconnective tissues proper

‚ùèdense connective tissue

‚ùèmore {{c1::fibers}}, less {{c2::cells and ground substance}} than loose CT

‚ùèdense irregular CT: collagen fibers arranged in multiple orientations, serving to {{c1::resist stress from all directions; elastic}} fibers often scattered among {{c2::collagen}};
‚ùèfound in {{c3::dermis of skin, sheaths of nerves, capsule of spleen, testes, ovaries, kidneys, and lymph nodes}}

Adipocytes and supporting connective tissue, blood vessels
